Technical Implementation Guide: Building an Agentic RAG Application

This guide outlines the architectural requirements and iterative development workflow for building a high-performance, agentic Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) system. Unlike "Naive RAG," which focuses on simple semantic similarity, Agentic RAG leverages a suite of tools—including multi-format parsing, text-to-SQL, and sub-agent orchestration—to provide grounded, accurate insights from complex datasets.

1. Introduction to Agentic RAG and the Development Philosophy

The shift from Naive RAG to Agentic RAG represents a move from static pipelines to dynamic, reasoning-led retrieval.

Comparison: Naive RAG vs. Agentic RAG

Feature	Naive RAG	Agentic RAG
Retrieval Mechanism	Pure Vector Search (Semantic)	Hybrid (Vector + BM25 + Text-to-SQL)
Control Logic	Fixed script/pipeline	Agent-driven tool selection and loops
Parsing	Basic text/Markdown extraction	Advanced (Dockling, VLM-based extraction)
Context Management	Static window stuffing	Dynamic context isolation via Sub-Agents
Capability	Surface-level similarity	Deep research, synthesis, and structured querying

The Collaborative AI Loop

Implementation follows the "Plan, Build, Validate, Iterate" cycle using Claude Code. This collaborative approach ensures that the solution evolves on a stable foundation rather than delegating the entire build to an autonomous loop that may drift from the PRD.

1. Plan: Use Claude Code's "Plan Mode" to define features and acceptance criteria.
2. Build: Execute the generation across frontend and backend layers.
3. Validate: Perform automated (Playwright) and manual smoke tests.
4. Iterate: Address edge cases by clearing context and refining specific logic.


